This contributes to low women's status in holistic terms with emphasis on women portraying a stereotypical role as mere nurturers of men [34]. Poor men expressed limited knowledge regarding pregnant women's legal rights to abortion in Jamaica. This is not surprising, given the view that pregnant women are socially perceived as wives fulfilling their primary role as mother of the family's children [35]. Similarly, in developing countries of Asia, women also suffered physical violence and discrimination from their husbands during pregnancy [36]. Women from families that are patriarchal tend to have limited opportunities and control over access to resources, which further affects women's access to services and information in general [37, 38].

Education of nurses is also important in order to increase awareness and break the stigma for clients regarding the moral dilemmas that are induced by initiation of abortion-related discussions.

Other prosocial situations

Although the healthcare environment can be a very egocentric place, and open discussions about abortion are conflicting to nurses, other elements with prosocial characteristics were described by those interviewed. These characteristics seem to be contradictory to the stigma in the study, but are pertinent to those in control of processes in the clinic in respect of this stigmatization.
